Neurological complications associated with HIV and AIDS: clinical implications 
for nursing.

Theroux N, Phipps M, Zimmerman L, Relf MV.

This article provides a clinical nursing update on major neurological 
complications associated with HIV and AIDS. Life expectancy for those with AIDS 
has increased as a consequence of antiretroviral therapy, and thus, neurological 
complications remain a clinical challenge. Four significant diseases associated 
with HIV and AIDS are addressed: HIV-associated dementia, peripheral neuropathy, 
cryptococcal meningitis, and toxoplasmosis. Updated statistics, a review of 
pathophysiology, common manifestations, diagnostic tests, and standard 
treatments are discussed for each disease. Nursing considerations when caring 
for this population are reviewed and include assessment, safety, activities of 
daily living, pain management, and treatment adherence.

